### [Lenape and New Netherland](/History_of_New_York_City_(prehistory%E2%80%931664)), to 1664

The indigenous [Munsee](/Munsee_language) called the southern tip of the island [Manhattoe](/Manhattoe). The Dutch, predictably, slapped their own name on it: New Amsterdam. Or sometimes just "Amsterdam." As if the world needed another one. The official city limits? They stopped at the wall. The one that eventually became [Wall Street](/Wall_Street). So, Manhattan north of that? Not really *their* New Amsterdam. Fascinating.

### History

#### Early exploration and settlement (1609–1624)

Before the Dutch, there was [Giovanni da Verrazzano](/Giovanni_da_Verrazzano) in 1524. He named it [Nouvelle Angoulême](/New_Angoul%C3%AAme) for some French king. Fancy. Then, in 1609, the [Dutch](/Dutch_Republic) sent [Henry Hudson](/Henry_Hudson) in the [Halve Maen](/Halve_Maen) – "Half Moon." He was supposed to find the [Northwest Passage](/Northwest_Passage) for the [Dutch East India Company](/Dutch_East_India_Company), but instead found a river he named the Mauritius River. More importantly, he found beaver. And where there’s beaver, there’s profit.

Beaver pelts. Essential for waterproof hats. And their glands? Used for medicine and perfume. Europeans went mad for it. So, expeditions by [Adriaen Block](/Adriaen_Block) and [Hendrick Christiaensen](/Hendrick_Christiaensen) followed. They mapped the area and, in 1614, called it New Netherland. They also established [Fort Nassau](/Fort_Nassau_(North_River)) – the first permanent Dutch presence. It was later replaced by Fort Orange, which became [Beverwijck](/Beverwijck), then [Albany](/Albany,_New_York).

And then there’s [Juan Rodriguez](/Juan_(Jan)_Rodriguez). Born in Santo Domingo, possibly of [Portuguese](/Portuguese_people) and [African](/List_of_ethnic_groups_of_Africa) descent. He was here in 1613–1614, trading with the locals for the Dutch. The first non-Indigenous person recorded in what would become New York City. A footnote, but a significant one.

New Netherland was initially just a private venture. A place to trade. To make money. Not a grand colonial vision, not yet.

#### Pilgrims' attempt to settle in the Hudson River area

The [Pilgrims](/Pilgrims_(Plymouth_Colony))? They tried to get to the Hudson River in 1620. The [Mayflower](/Mayflower) landed at [Cape Cod](/Cape_Cod) instead. Supplies were low, and they just… stayed. Established the [Plymouth Colony](/Plymouth_Colony). Tough luck for them.

#### Dutch return

The mouth of the [Hudson River](/Hudson_River) was the prime spot. Access to the ocean, and a clear path to the beaver trade upriver. Indigenous hunters brought pelts, Dutch brought trinkets and [wampum](/Wampum). The [Dutch West India Company](/Dutch_West_India_Company) got serious in 1621. Private traders were out; settlers and company men were in. The laws of Holland applied. No more ship's law.

May 20, 1624. Thirty families arrived on Noten Eylandt (now [Governors Island](/Governors_Island)) aboard the Nieu Nederlandt, under [Cornelius Jacobsen May](/Cornelius_Jacobsen_May). They claimed the territory. This landing brought the "legal and cultural DNA" of the [Dutch Republic](/Dutch_Republic) – ideas like freedom of conscience and tolerance. Compared to Europe, it was progressive. Various nationalities, religions, races coexisted. Popular sovereignty, free trade. Sounds almost idyllic. Almost. They also brought slavery, starting in 1626. So, you know, progress with caveats.

Engineer Crijn Fredericxsz was tasked with building [Fort Amsterdam](/Fort_Amsterdam). Completed in 1626.

These families were scattered: to [Fort Wilhelmus](/Fort_Wilhelmus) on the [Delaware River](/Delaware_River), to Kievitshoek on the [Connecticut River](/Connecticut_River), and upriver to [Fort Nassau](/Fort_Nassau_(North_River)) on the [Hudson River](/Hudson_River).

They even built windmills. Franchoys Fezard constructed one on Nut Island. Later dismantled for iron. Resourceful. Or desperate.

#### Fort Amsterdam (1624)

Threatened by other European powers, the [Dutch West India Company](/Dutch_West_India_Company) decided to protect the Hudson River entrance. In 1624, 30 families moved to Manhattan. [Cryn Frederickz van Lobbrecht](/Cryn_Frederickz_van_Lobbrecht) laid out [Fort Amsterdam](/Fort_Amsterdam) under [Willem Verhulst](/Willem_Verhulst). By 1625, it was staked out south of [Bowling Green](/Bowling_Green_(New_York_City)). The [Mohawk-Mahican War](/Beaver_Wars) spurred more settlers. Colonizing was expensive, the fur trade only subsidized it so much. Plans were scaled back. By 1628, a smaller fort was built, walls of clay and sand.

It was the hub: barracks, church, director's house, warehouse. Troops marched between [Heerestraat](/Broadway_(Manhattan)) and [Whitehall Street](/Whitehall_Street). Standard military stuff.

#### 1624–1664

[Peter Minuit](/Peter_Minuit) replaced Verhulst in 1626. He negotiated the "purchase" of Manhattan from the [Canarse](/Metoac) for 60 [guilders](/Dutch_guilder) worth of goods. A band of them occupied the southern tip. Minuit dealt with Chief Seyseys. He was happy to trade for shiny things. An island mostly controlled by the Weckquaesgeeks, apparently.

A letter from Pieter Schagen on November 7, 1626, informed the [States General](/States_General_of_the_Netherlands) of the purchase. 60 guilders. About $1,100 in 2012 dollars. Not exactly a steal, especially considering the land wasn't exclusively theirs to sell. The deed? Lost to time. The legend of $24 worth of trinkets? Mostly myth.

Windmills appeared. For sawmills, exploiting the timber. Later, they harnessed creek power. A sawmill at 74th Street and [Second Avenue](/Second_Avenue_(Manhattan)) used African slaves for lumber. Progress.

The [Castello Plan](/Castello_Plan), a 1660 map, shows New Amsterdam. The fort gave [The Battery](/Battery_Park) its name. The main street became [Broadway](/Broadway_(Manhattan)). The city wall? [Wall Street](/Wall_Street). Simple.

The population was around 270. In 1642, Director [Willem Kieft](/Willem_Kieft) built a stone church inside the fort. Finished in 1645. Destroyed in the [Slave Insurrection of 1741](/New_York_Conspiracy_of_1741). Predictable.

A pen-and-ink view from 1648, found in Vienna. Shows New Amsterdam from Capske Rock. Associated with [Adriaen van der Donck](/Adriaen_van_der_Donck)'s Remonstrance.

New Amsterdam became a city on February 2, 1653. It got its [municipal rights](/Town_privileges) from Governor Peter Stuyvesant. Albany (then Beverwyck) got its rights in 1652. [Harlem](/Harlem) was recognized in 1658.

The first Dutch [Jews](/Jews) arrived in 1654. Solomon Pietersen and Jacob Barsimson. Then, in September, 23 refugees from [Recife](/Recife), Brazil. Director-general Stuyvesant wanted to turn them away. The Dutch West India Company said no. [Asser Levy](/Asser_Levy), one of the refugees, became the first Jew to own property in New Amsterdam in 1661. A milestone.

September 15, 1655. Hundreds of [Munsee](/Munsee) occupied New Amsterdam. It started with a Dutch colonist killing a woman stealing peaches. Then fighting broke out. Farms destroyed, 40 dead, 100 captured. The [Peach War](/Peach_War). Charming name.

The [Communipaw ferry](/Communipaw_ferry) started in 1661. A long history of transportation.

In 1664, Jan van Bonnel built a [sawmill](/Sawmill) on 74th Street. It used a stream called the Saw Kill. Later owners converted it to a leather mill. The Saw Kill was eventually culverted. Gone. Like most of the original buildings.

***

#### English capture

August 27, 1664. England and the Dutch Republic were at peace. Four English frigates sailed in. Demanded surrender. They got it. Bloodless [capture of New Amsterdam](/Capture_of_New_Amsterdam). Stuyvesant’s lawyer, [Johannes de Decker](/Johannes_de_Decker), and five others signed the [Articles of Surrender of New Netherland](/Articles_of_Surrender_of_New_Netherland).

Then came the [Second Anglo-Dutch War](/Second_Anglo-Dutch_War). In June 1665, New Amsterdam became New York. Named after the [Duke of York](/Duke_of_York) (brother of [King Charles II](/Charles_II_of_England)).

The [Treaty of Breda](/Treaty_of_Breda_(1667)) ended the war. The Dutch gave up New Netherland. The English kept it. The Dutch got control of [Surinam](/Surinam_(Dutch_colony)) in South America. A trade.

August 9, 1673. [Third Anglo-Dutch War](/Third_Anglo-Dutch_War). The Dutch retook it. Briefly. [Jacob Benckes](/Jacob_Binckes) and [Cornelis Evertsen de Jongste](/Cornelis_Evertsen_the_Youngest) were in command. [Anthony Colve](/Anthony_Colve) became the first Dutch governor. New York was renamed New Orange.

But then, the [Treaty of Westminster](/Treaty_of_Westminster_(1674)). February 1674. Both sides relinquished claims. November 10, 1674, control passed back to the English. New Orange became New York again. Suriname officially became Dutch.

